The Telegraph - Calcutta : Metro

 The City Diary

 A division bench of Calcutta High Court rejected on Monday the bail petition of the five former constables of Calcutta Armed Police, who have been convicted of murdering sergeant Bapi Sen two years ago. Pijush Goswami, Sreedam Bauri, Sheikh Mujibar Rahaman, Sekhar Bhusan Mitra and Madhusudan Chakraborty have been sentenced to life imprisonment by the trial court. 

 he constables, all drunk, had beaten up Bapi when he tried to stop them from harassing an unidentified woman on New Year?s eve. Sen had been admitted to a clinic with serious injuries, to which he succumbed a few days later. The bail plea of the five was rejected by a bench of Justice N.A. Chowdhury and Justice Arun Kumar Bhattacharjee. 

 Jhunu Karmakar, 50, died of the injuries she sustained in the head after falling off a minibus on the Brabourne Road flyover on Monday evening. Karmakar, a resident of Liluah, fell off the footboard of the bus around 4.15 pm. 

 olice said the driver was trying to overtake another bus when a private car swerved in his way, forcing him to slam the brakes abruptly. The sudden lurch disbalanced Karmakar, who was thrown on to the road.

 o escape public ire, the driver and the conductors of the bus fled from the scene. Karmakar was taken to Calcutta Medical College and Hospital, where doctors declared her dead. The minibus was impounded.

 Autorickshaws were off the streets in Behala, New Alipore and their adjacent areas on Monday, following a clash between the drivers and local traders at the Behala-New Alipore crossing.

 he trouble started after an autorickshaw hit a cyclist at the spot. Two autorickshaw drivers were arrested for attacking policemen and damaging a number of shops.

 A fire broke out at a Tangra slum on Sunday night, injuring seven persons. While four of the injured have been admitted to NRS Medical College and Hospital, others were discharged after first-aid.

 Two elderly persons were knocked down on VIP Road, near Kaikhali, on Monday afternoon by a loaded oil tanker. Upendra Podder, 70, and Sailarani Pal, 65, died on the spot. Police said the two were trying to cross the road when they were hit by the tanker. Local residents blocked Jessore Road in protest. The blockade was lifted after half-an-hour.

 Binayak Health World unveiled on Monday its state-of-the-art imaging and diagnostic centre in Sinthee. Left Front chairman Biman Bose inaugurated the centre in the presence of PWD minister Amar Chowdhury and transport minister Subhas Chakraborty.

 A middle-aged man, Shankar Pal, was detained by police on Monday evening at Narayantala, near Baguiati, for felling trees on VIP Road. Police said Shankar was caught red-handed. He had chopped off the branches of some trees and kept them in bundles. 

 ccording to Goutam Mitra, officer-in-charge of Baguiati police station, several local residents had complained that Shankar was felling trees in the neighbourhood. 

 A meeting was held on Monday at Writers Buildings to realise Rs 621 crore revenue from the transport sector in Calcutta and adjoining areas. The meeting, at the Rotunda, was attended by finance minister Asim Dasgupta, transport minister Subhas Chakraborty and the district magistrates of Howrah, North and South 24-Parganas.

